From what I gather the problem is that `device.connect()` doesn&#39;t error correctly so will just silently die and the `catch` will not work properly.

If so you could wrap `device.connect()` in another promise with a timeout to `reject`.

This gist would do the trick. Javascript Promise Timeout.
https://gist.github.com/john-doherty/bcf35d39d8b30d01ae51ccdecf6c94f5

The only problem being you can&#39;t actually cancel `device.connect()` so it may be doing something strange in the background after you think it has stopped or it maybe a problem to re-try. The best thing would be to check out the `device.connect()` and see if you can pass it a callback that can actually reject the promise. If you can&#39;t this should work.

```
function promiseTimeout(ms, promise){

  return new Promise(function(resolve, reject){

    // create a timeout to reject promise if not resolved
    var timer = setTimeout(function(){
        reject(
            // Do whatever you want here after the timeout            
        );
    }, ms);

    promise
        .then(function(res){
            clearTimeout(timer);
            resolve(res);
        })
        .catch(function(err){
            clearTimeout(timer);
            reject(err);
        });
  });
};

